{"title_page": "List of diplomatic missions of the United States", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n\n[[File:US embassies 2007.png|thumb|right|400px|The United States of America (green) and its diplomatic missions, including embassies (blue), interests sections, and other representations (light blue)]]\n\nThe United States has the most [[diplomatic mission]]s of any country in the world,<ref>https://www.lowyinstitute.org/global-diplomacy-index/country_rank.html,</ref>\nincluding 169<!--excepting 24 -- [5 Africa] Comoros, G. Bissau, Libya, St Tome, Seychelles, [4 America] Dominica, St Kitts, St Lucia, St Vincent, [6 Asia] Bhutan, Iran, Maldives, North Korea, Syria, Yemen, [4 Europe] Andorra, Liechtenstein, Monaco, San Marino, [5 Oceania] Kiribati, Nauru, Tonga, Tuvalu, Vanuatu--> of the 193 member countries of the [[United Nations]], as well as observer state Vatican City and non-member countries of [[Kosovo]] and [[Taiwan]]. It maintains \"interest sections\" (in other states' embassies) in member states Iran and Syria.\n\n==History==\n[[Morocco]], in December 1777, became the first nation to seek diplomatic relations with the [[United States]] and together they maintain the United States' longest unbroken [[Moroccan\u2013American Treaty of Friendship|treaty]].<ref>{{cite book|date=April 1, 2006|publisher=International Business Publications, USA|location=Washington, DC|page=94|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8GjrAeMS1dIC&pg=PA94|accessdate=17 August 2014|title=Morocco Country Study Guide}}</ref>\n\n[[Benjamin Franklin]] established the first overseas mission of the United States in [[Paris]] in 1779. On April 19, 1782, [[John Adams]] was received by the [[States-General of the Netherlands|States-General]] and the [[Dutch Republic]] as they were the first country, together with Morocco and France, to recognize the United States as an independent government.  John Adams then became the first [[United States Ambassador to the Netherlands|U.S. ambassador to the Netherlands]]<ref>[http://thehague.usembassy.gov/speeches_editorials.html Speeches and editorials 2007 \u2013 U.S. Embassy The Hague, Netherlands] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612181705/http://thehague.usembassy.gov/speeches_editorials.html |date=June 12, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geheugenvannederland.nl/?%2Fen%2Fcollecties%2Fatlantic_world=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127065503/http://www.geheugenvannederland.nl/?%2Fen%2Fcollecties%2Fatlantic_world=|url-status=dead|title=Atlantic World \u2013 Collections \u2013 Memory of the Netherlands \u2013 Online ima\u2026|date=5 July 2015|archivedate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.masshist.org/adams/timeline.cfm |title=The Adams Timeline |publisher=The Massachusetts Historical Society |accessdate=2012-10-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806125722/http://www.masshist.org/adams/timeline.cfm |archivedate=2011-08-06 }}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20081206053301/http://www.john-adams.nl/theinstitute/history.html The John Adams Institute, American culture and literature, Lectures<!-- Bot generated title -->](archive)</ref> and the house that he had purchased at Fluwelen Burgwal 18 in [[The Hague]], became the first U.S. embassy anywhere in the world.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061230154418/http://www.usembassy.nl/friendship_days2.html US embassy report on Dutch-American Friendship Day.] (archive)</ref>\n\nIn the period following the [[American Revolution]], [[George Washington]] sent a number of close advisers to the courts of European potentates in order to garner recognition of U.S. independence with mixed results, including [[Thomas Jefferson]], [[John Adams]], [[Francis Dana]], and [[John Jay]].<ref>[[United States Department of State]], Timeline of U.S. Diplomatic History, [https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ho/time/ar/ 1775\u20131783 Diplomacy and the American Revolution]. Accessed 29 August 2008.</ref> Much of the first fifty years of the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]] concerned negotiating with imperial European powers over the territorial integrity of the borders of the United States as known today.\n\nThe first overseas consulate of the fledgling United States was founded in 1790 at [[Consulate of the United States, Liverpool|Liverpool, Great Britain]], by [[James Maury (consul)|James Maury Jr.]], who was appointed by Washington. Maury held the post from 1790 to 1829. Liverpool was at the time Britain's leading port for transatlantic commerce and therefore of great economic importance to the [[United States]].  President George Washington, on November 19, 1792, nominated Benjamin Joy of Newbury Port as the first [[Consulate General of the United States, Kolkata|U.S. Consul to Kolkata]] (then Calcutta), India.  Joy was not recognized as consul by the British East India Company but was permitted to \u201creside here as a Commercial Agent subject to the Civil and Criminal Jurisdiction of this Country\u2026\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://in.usembassy.gov/embassy-consulates/kolkata/|title=U.S. Consulate General Kolkata {{!}} U.S. Embassy & Consulates in India|newspaper=U.S. Embassy & Consulates in India|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-02}}</ref>  The first overseas property owned, and the longest continuously owned, by the United States is the [[American Legation, Tangier|American Legation in Tangier]], which was a gift of the [[Sultan of Morocco]] in 1821.  In general during the nineteenth century, the United States' diplomatic activities were done on a minimal budget.  The U.S. owned no property abroad and provided no official residences for its foreign envoys, paid them a minimal salary, and gave them the rank of ministers rather than ambassadors who represented the [[great power]]s\u2014a position which the U.S. only achieved towards the end of the nineteenth century.<ref name=\"Loeffler\">{{cite book |last=Loeffler |first=Jane C. |title=Architecture of Diplomacy: Building America |url=https://archive.org/details/architectureofdi0000loef |url-access=registration |publisher=Princeton Architectural Press |year=1998 |page=[https://archive.org/details/architectureofdi0000loef/page/13 13] }}</ref>\n\nIn the latter half of the nineteenth century, the State Department was concerned with expanding commercial ties in Asia, establishing [[Liberia]], foiling [[diplomatic recognition]] of the [[Confederate States of America]] during the [[American Civil War]], and securing its presence in North America. The Confederacy had diplomatic missions in the United Kingdom, France, Belgium, the [[Papal States]], Russia, Mexico, and Spain, and consular missions in Ireland, Canada, Cuba, Italy, Bermuda, and [[Bahamas|Nassau and New Providence]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.mss/eadmss.ms003052 |title=Confederate States of America records, 1854\u20131889 |publisher=Library of Congress |date= |access-date=2012-10-25 }}</ref>\n\nThe United States' global prominence became evident in the twentieth century, and the State Department was required to invest in a large network of diplomatic missions to manage its bilateral and multilateral relations.<ref>[[United States Department of State]], [http://usembassy.state.gov Websites of U.S. Embassies, Consulates, and Diplomatic Missions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205090859/http://usembassy.state.gov/. |date=2008-12-05 }}.  Accessed 29 August 2008.</ref>  The wave of overseas construction began with the creation of the State Department's Foreign Service Buildings Commission in 1926.<ref name=\"Loeffler\"/>\n\n==Africa==\nThe U.S. has embassies (or, in the case of Seychelles, a Consular Agency) in all states it recognizes with the exceptions of the Comoros, Guinea-Bissau, Libya, and Sao Tome.\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*{{DZA}}\n** [[Algiers]] (Embassy)\n*{{AGO}}\n** [[Luanda]] (Embassy)\n*{{BEN}}\n** [[Cotonou]] (Embassy)\n*{{BWA}}\n** [[Gaborone]] (Embassy)\n*{{BFA}}\n** [[Ouagadougou]] (Embassy)\n*{{BDI}}\n** [[Bujumbura]] (Embassy)\n*{{CMR}}\n** [[Yaound\u00e9]] (Embassy)\n** [[Douala]] (Embassy Branch Office)\n*{{CPV}}\n** [[Praia]] (Embassy)\n*{{CAF}}\n** [[Bangui]] (Embassy)\n*{{TCD}}\n** [[N'Djamena]] (Embassy)\n*{{COG}}\n** [[Brazzaville]] (Embassy)\n*{{COD}}\n** [[Kinshasa]] (Embassy)\n*{{DJI}}\n** [[Djibouti (city)|Djibouti]] (Embassy)\n*{{EGY}}\n** [[Cairo]] (Embassy)\n*{{GNQ}}\n** [[Malabo]] ([[Embassy of the United States, Malabo|Embassy]])\n*{{ERI}}\n** [[Asmara]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Eswatini}}\n** [[Mbabane]] (Embassy)\n*{{ETH}}\n** [[Addis Ababa]] (Embassy)\n*{{GAB}}\n** [[Libreville]] (Embassy)\n*{{GMB}}\n** [[Banjul]] (Embassy)\n*{{GHA}}\n** [[Accra]] (Embassy)\n*{{GIN}}\n** [[Conakry]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Ivory Coast}}\n** [[Abidjan]] (Embassy)\n*{{KEN}}\n** [[Nairobi]] ([[Embassy of the United States, Nairobi|Embassy]])\n*{{LSO}}\n** [[Maseru]] (Embassy)\n*{{LBR}}\n** [[Monrovia]] (Embassy)\n*{{MDG}}\n** [[Antananarivo]] (Embassy)\n*{{MWI}}\n** [[Lilongwe]] (Embassy)\n*{{MLI}}\n** [[Bamako]] (Embassy)\n*{{MRT}}\n** [[Nouakchott]] (Embassy)\n*{{MUS}}\n** [[Port Louis]] (Embassy)\n*{{MAR}}\n** [[Rabat]] (Embassy)\n** [[Casablanca]] (Consulate General)\n*{{MOZ}}\n** [[Maputo]] (Embassy)\n*{{NAM}}\n** [[Windhoek]] (Embassy)\n*{{NER}}\n** [[Niamey]] (Embassy)\n*{{NGA}}\n** [[Abuja]] (Embassy)\n** [[Lagos]] (Consulate General)\n*{{RWA}}\n** [[Kigali]] (Embassy)\n*{{SEN}}\n** [[Dakar]] (Embassy)\n*{{SEY}}\n** [[Victoria, Seychelles|Victoria]] (Consular Agency)\n*{{SLE}}\n** [[Freetown]] (Embassy)\n*{{SOM}}\n** [[Mogadishu]] ([[Embassy of the United States, Mogadishu|Embassy]])\n*{{ZAF}}\n** [[Pretoria]] ([[Embassy of the United States, Pretoria|Embassy]])\n** [[Cape Town]] (Consulate General)\n** [[Durban]] (Consulate General)\n** [[Johannesburg]] (Consulate General)\n*{{SSD}}\n** [[Juba]] ([[Embassy of the United States, Juba|Embassy]])\n*{{SDN}}\n** [[Khartoum]] (Embassy)\n*{{TZA}}\n** [[Dar es Salaam]] ([[Embassy of the United States, Dar es Salaam|Embassy]])\n*{{TGO}}\n** [[Lom\u00e9]] (Embassy)\n*{{TUN}}\n** [[Tunis]] (Embassy)\n*{{UGA}}\n** [[Kampala]] (Embassy)\n*{{ZMB}}\n** [[Lusaka]] (Embassy)\n*{{ZWE}}\n** [[Harare]] (Embassy)\n{{div col end}}\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"160\">\nFile:American embassy in Antananarivo, Madagascar.jpg|U.S. Embassy in [[Antananarivo]]\nFile:American Embassy in Dar Es Salaam.jpg|[[Embassy of the United States, Dar es Salaam|U.S. Embassy in Dar es Salaam]]\nFile:Embassy of the United States in Swaziland.jpg|U.S. Embassy in [[Ezulwini Valley|Ezulwini]], [[Eswatini|Eswatini (formerly known as Swaziland)]]\nFile:Chancery.jpg|U.S. Embassy in [[Libreville]]\nFile:US Embassy Nairobi.jpg|U.S. Embassy in [[Nairobi]]\nFile:Yaound\u00e9 ambaixada EUA.jpg|U.S. Embassy in [[Yaound\u00e9]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Americas==\nThe U.S. has embassies (or, in the case of  Antigua & Barbuda, a Consular Agency) in all states it recognizes with the exceptions of Dominica, St Kitts & Nevis, St Lucia and St Vincent.\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*{{ATG}}\n** [[St. John's, Antigua and Barbuda|St. John's]] (Consular Agency)\n*{{ARG}}\n** [[Buenos Aires]] (Embassy)\n*{{BHS}}\n** [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]] (Embassy)\n*{{BRB}}\n** [[Bridgetown]] (Embassy)\n*{{BLZ}}\n** [[Belmopan]] (Embassy)\n*{{BOL}}\n** [[La Paz]] (Embassy)\n** [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]] (Consular Agency)\n*{{BRA}}\n** [[Bras\u00edlia]] (Embassy)\n** [[Recife]] (Consulate General)\n** [[Rio de Janeiro]] (Consulate General)\n** [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] (Consulate General)\n** [[Belo Horizonte]] (Embassy Branch Office)\n** [[Fortaleza]] (Consular Agency)\n** [[Manaus]] (Consular Agency)\n** [[Porto Alegre]] (Consulate) \n** [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]] (Consular Agency)\n*{{CAN}}\n** [[Ottawa]] ([[Embassy of the United States, Ottawa|Embassy]])\n** [[Calgary]] (Consulate General)\n** [[Halifax (former city), Nova Scotia|Halifax]] (Co