ert|50|kg|lb|abbr=on}} under-wing.\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent|\n|related= \n* [[Junkers Ju 187]]\n|similar aircraft=\n* [[Aichi D3A]]\n* [[Aichi B7A Ryusei]]\n* [[Blackburn Skua]]\n* [[Breda Ba.65]]\n* [[Breda Ba.201]]\n* [[Brewster SB2A Buccaneer]]\n* [[Curtiss SB2C Helldiver]]\n* [[Douglas SBD Dauntless]]\n* [[Fairey Barracuda]]\n* [[Ilyushin Il-2]]\n* [[Loire-Nieuport LN.401]]\n* [[Nakajima B5N]]\n* [[Nakajima B6N Tenzan]]\n* [[Saab 17]]\n* [[Vultee A-31 Vengeance]]\n* [[Yokosuka D4Y Suisei]]\n|lists=\n* [[List of aircraft of World War II]]\n* [[List of military aircraft of Germany]]\n* [[List of bomber aircraft]]\n|see also=\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n*{{note label|Note1|a|a}} Figures are debated. Griehl cites additions of Chief engineer Pichon's list. This indicates 5,930 produced. Griehl points out this may include all machines, even those that were incomplete. Junkers records give 5,126 aircraft delivered to the Luftwaffe.<ref>{{harvnb|Griehl|2001|pp=129\u2013130}}</ref>\n* {{note label|Note2|b|b}} The first of Germany's allies to receive Stukas was Italy. Regia Aeronautica received a delivery of 46 Ju 87 D-2 and D-3 dive bombers and some Ju 87 R-2s.<ref>{{harvnb|Vanags-Baginskis|1982|p=52}}</ref> Bulgaria received 12 Ju 87 R-2 and R-4s and 40 Ju 87 D-5s.<ref>{{harvnb|Griehl|2001|p=135}}</ref> Japan received the Ju 87 A-1 (called a Ju 87 K-1). The Croats received Ju 87s, delivered to the ''Lucko'' bomber unit in January 1944. The Romanians received 90 Ju 87 D-3 and D-5s.<ref>{{harvnb|Griehl|2001|p=150}}</ref> Hungary received 33/34 Ju 87 D-3/D-5s and 11/12 B-1 and B-2s.<ref>{{harvnb|Griehl|2001|pp=151\u2013152}}</ref> The Slovaks received unknown numbers of Ju 87s. After the war it is claimed five Ju 87 D-5s, registrations OK-XAA \u2013 OK-XAE, were operated by the Czechs after the war as \"B-37\" registration OK-KAC.<ref>{{harvnb|Griehl|2001|p=156}}</ref>\n* {{note label|Note3|c|c}} ''Werknummer'' (W.Nr) means \"Works Number\" of the factory. The number can usually be found on the vertical stabiliser of all German military aircraft of the Second World War.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bergstr\u00f6m|first=Christer|title=Bagration to Berlin \u2013 The Final Air Battles in the East: 1944\u20131945|location=London|publisher=Ian Allan|year=2008|isbn=978-1-903223-91-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bergstr\u00f6m|first=Christer|title=Barbarossa \u2013 The Air Battle: July\u2013December 1941|location=London|publisher=Chevron/Ian Allan|year=2007|isbn=978-1-85780-270-2}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bergstr\u00f6m|first=Christer|title=Kursk \u2013 The Air Battle: July 1943|location=London|publisher=Chevron/Ian Allan|year=2007|isbn=978-1-903223-88-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bergstr\u00f6m|first=Christer|title=Stalingrad \u2013 The Air Battle: November 1942\u2013February 1943|location=London|publisher=Chevron/Ian Allan|year=2007|isbn=978-1-85780-276-4}}.\n* {{cite book|last=Boyne|first=W. J.|title=Clash of Wings|url=https://archive.org/details/clashofwingsairp00boyn|url-access=registration|location=New York|publisher=Simon & Schuster|year=1994|isbn=0-684-83915-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bungay|first=Stephen|title=The Most Dangerous Enemy: A History of the Battle of Britain|location=London|publisher=Aurum|year=2000|isbn=1-85410-721-6}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Ciglic|first1=Boris|last2=Savic|first2=Dragan|title=Dornier Do 17 \u2013 The Yugoslav Story: Operational Record 1937\u20131947|location=Belgrade|publisher=Jeroplan|year=2007|isbn=978-86-909727-0-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Coram|first=Robert|title=Boyd: The Fighter Pilot Who Changed the Art of War|location=New York|publisher=Back Bay Books|year=2004|isbn=0-316-79688-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/boyd00robe}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Dressel|first1=Joachim|last2=Griehl|first2=Manfred|title=Bombers of the Luftwaffe |location=London |publisher=DAG |year=1994 |isbn=1-85409-140-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Erfurth|first=Helmut|title